ting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mutton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Cornwall and Northamptonshire):","nickname from Middle English <i>motoun</i> ‘sheep’ (Old French <i>mouton</i>).","variant of   Mitton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Moton","meanings":["English: variant of   Mutton  .","Probably also an altered form of English   Morton  ."]},{"name":"Motton","meanings":["English (Cornwall and Devon): variant of   Mutton  ."]},{"name":"Mitton","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): habitational name from any of the places in Lancashire, Yorkshire, and the West Midlands, so named in Old English as ‘farmstead at a river confluence’, from <i>(ge)m̄ȳthe</i> ‘river confluence’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]},{"name":"Mouton","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Antoine, Camille, Elphege, Emile, Michel, Ravis, Adhemar, Adrien, Alcee, Alcide.","French: nickname from Old French <i>mouton</i> ‘sheep’, used for a docile, mild-mannered person, for someone easily led, or perhaps for a curly-haired man. This surname is also established in South Africa.","English: variant of   Mutton  ."]},{"name":"Moden","meanings":["Swedish (<b>Modén</b>): ornamental or topographic name from <i>mo</i> ‘sandy heath’ + the adjectival suffix <i>-én</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>-enius</i> ‘relating to’, with intrusive <i>-d-</i> for euphony.","English: variant of   Mutton  ."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":40,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":49,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger de Mutton was born in 1175, in Wilton, Wiltshire, England, his father, Sir Hugh de Mutton Knight, was 21 and his mother, Olive de Goosnargh, was 20. He married Ameria Anna Hussey in 1200, in London, Middlesex, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1225, in London, Middlesex, England, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1175–1225":"1175–1225","1179–Male":"1179–Surnud","1180–1225":"1180–1225","1200–1250":"1200–1250","1154–1209":"1154–1209","1155–Female":"1155–Surnud","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","1200":"1200","1155":"1155","1154":"1154","1175":"1175","1173":"1173","1